snippet.textDisplay: I'm an optimist by nature but last year I had a big breakdown and, similar to Jack, the bad thoughts made me snap and think "this is not myself, I don't want this for myself". It actually happened two weeks after I had started therapy, which I started because I was feeling so empty and I thought there was something wrong with me. Now I look back and laugh at myself then for thinking I was doing things wrong or that something was wrong with me. My mind was playing tricks due to my home environment and life (in retrospective) wasn't half as bad as I believed it was. Thanks to therapy I slowly learnt how to understand and deal with different situations from life. I'm 25 years old. Still going to therapy. It's so helpful!

snippet.textDisplay:
First, thank you for the open, honesty. Even being a big YouTube name it's hard to open up to people sometimes. Shoutout to everyone who has pushed through their tough times and made it to 2020. I hope you have many more years to come.
Also I hate when people assume you can't be nice in person. My work is different, but I go to work at a nursing home and try to be a cheerful person, especially around my residents, and people think I'm fake because "no one can be that happy all the time." Like I try to live by your day is as good as you make it...

snippet.textDisplay: I know most people probably won’t care about what I have to say but I’m feeling the first 7 minutes of this video so fucking much, recently I was diagnosed with depression and anxiety which changed everything. It’s a constant thing that makes me feel like a failure and as though no one would ever miss me in a million years. I feel so numb all the time and even when I go to college to do stuff I love it’s like all of the feeling has been sucked out of it. I’ve thought about suicide, I’ve self harmed, I’ve pushed people away and shut myself down emotionally because I thought it was the best way to cope and a part of me still does, certain people in my life aren’t helping me and some people are. What I’m trying to say is that we’re all still fighting these urges no matter how big or small they might be and it’s going to take a long time to defeat them with or without any help so we shouldn’t have to suffer alone or have to apologise for being human. Just remember that Jack, you are loved by so many and so much. More than I could ever hope to be.

I dont really have that many friends and my only solace is in the internet really and video games. That's been my happiness really and living where I live doesn't help either with my shitty internet. I dont own a console wait I do but it's my old ps2 which doesn't work anymore so I guess I dont have any really. I'm so lonely its unreal sometimes i just in my room and cry. I know that may be weak and I'm not asking for anyone's pity I'm just sharing this so that if someone feels the same way at least THEY are not alone. My family isn't a good place either and we are struggling financially so that doesn't help either. I have thought of killing myself and wondering if someone would actually miss but I have never had the courage to do it, I'm not sure if that's weakness or something else it's been like this for a long time but in all honesty it's not really any different now. I have always wished to have friends like you see in those "me and the boys memes" but that just not plausible at the moment maybe in the future. Who knows?? But yeah I'm ranting now but this has been my experience with these type of thoughts

snippet.textDisplay:
I've never really had the thought that I didn't know what I was gonna do for the future. I mean, if you mean me thinking I should kill myself and not grow up, definitely.
I've been known as a big planner from people, I'm a leader and have gone through a lot of shit I've had to get over my whole life.
I've always known I wanted to write stories and make universes of characters and 2D animate(still waiting on that animating/drawing tablet tho). I've always known what the best for me was. Im writing music, teaching myself things and finding more things about the world.
Of course, some of this had lead me to hate the world and have a 'fuck you' attitude towards things, but I feel like I like being seen as a young woman that knows how to fight. I like being seen as strong. Its great because then you can get early jobs easily cause the managers would see you are willing to do your job.
Idk, the point of this comment is that I just never had the thought of being scared what would happen for me in the future. I just always knew what I wanted in life and to move on.
Love you, Sean. Your mental health talks really help me and make my days the best when I'm down, no joke, you would be the best big bro. <3

snippet.textDisplay: Personally, I'm here for any of the people I watch as a person. Not just content. In fact, I see them as people first. Some of the content is meh, but I've grown to respect them as people, or they make me laugh, or I can relate to them. If you are feeling sad, having a bad day, etc, go ahead and tell us. You have more support than you know. You are human, with real emotions. And that is perfectly okay. You could always start a vlogging channel for that kind of stuff. snippet.textOriginal: Personally, I'm here for any of the people I watch as a person. Not just content. In fact, I see them as people first. Some of the content is meh, but I've grown to respect them as people, or they make me laugh, or I can relate to them. If you are feeling sad, having a bad day, etc, go ahead and tell us. You have more support than you know. You are human, with real emotions. And that is perfectly okay. You could always start a vlogging channel for that kind of stuff. I think you might be surprised just how many subscribers follow you to that channel as well.

snippet.textDisplay: Hay Jack. Hearing your story really  helps me right now. I can relate really well to the one about you dropping out of college and feeling like you have no friends. I'm homeschooled and have one more year to go before graduation, I know what I want to do but am having a hard time getting there, and most of my days are spent cooped up in my room grinding away at something that doesn't ultemetly contribute to my future. I'm kinda lonely right now and even though I have family I'm still feeling like there's no one around. I see so many people on social media acting like they have it all but I always forget that people's lives are just not perfect and all we see is a 30 second video of them doing something amazing. Thanks for sharing this. I don't know why I didn't subscribe to you longer ago but I am now.

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you so much for posting this. I always thought I was the only one who thought like this. I tried to talk to my family, and friends about my doubts and fears. My family really didn't understand, but most of my friends that I met in college feel this way and others don't. My family doesn't understand what is going on with me. I went to college for Theater Arts and Dance and didn't do anything with it. It really put me in a dark place because I wanted to succeed so badly. But life came and crushed me hard, and now I'm in school for programming. Now with this degree, I'm 5 months away from graduating and I'm a bit nervous. However, I feel a bit different from graduating this time then what I did last time. I think I'm a bit more passionate about doing this but also a little self-conscious about my skills. I have a problem comparing myself to other people. Anyway, hearing you, following you and just being part of this community you built really helped me get through a lot of stressful days for the last 5 years.  Thank you.

snippet.textDisplay: I’ve been a long time viewer since about 2013-2014 when I was only about 7 years old. Sean you made my entire childhood absolutely amazing. I watched your videos every time I came home from school and when I remember watching the turbo dismount videos or the goat simulator videos, I get the best feeling out of it because I just look back and I remember being a care free kid that just loved to have fun. Even with a bad home environment you made each day a little bit brighter and when I got out of school I always had something to look forward to. During these times of depression where you just feel as if life is meaningless or you just can’t find happiness, think about all of the childhoods you shaped and the people you influenced and made happy. I love you Sean you made some of the best years of my life
